# Code Style and Conciseness

## General Principles

- Keep code condensed and minimal while maintaining readability
- Use clear, descriptive variable names that convey purpose
- Avoid unnecessary verbosity or redundant code

## Variable Usage

- Only create variables if they are used **more than twice**
- For single-use values, inline them directly where needed
- For values used exactly twice, evaluate if extraction improves readability

### Examples

```typescript
// ❌ Bad - variable used only once
const userName = user.name;
console.log(userName);

// ✅ Good - inline single-use values
console.log(user.name);

// ❌ Bad - variable used twice but doesn't improve clarity
const isValid = value > 0;
if (isValid) return isValid;

// ✅ Good - inline when clarity is maintained
if (value > 0) return value > 0;

// ✅ Good - variable used multiple times
const sanitizedInput = input.trim().toLowerCase();
if (sanitizedInput.length === 0) return;
processInput(sanitizedInput);
logInput(sanitizedInput);
```

## File Management

- **Do not create summary files** or unnecessary documentation files
- Avoid creating helper files unless absolutely necessary
- Keep related functionality together rather than over-abstracting

## Readability Guidelines

While being concise:
- Use meaningful names for functions, variables, and types
- Keep function names descriptive and purposeful
- Maintain proper code formatting and structure
- Add comments only when the code's intent isn't immediately clear
